---
description: Use Portolan before making codebase map or architecture claims.
globs:
  - "**/*"
alwaysApply: false
---

When the user asks to map, audit, inspect, understand, or explain this
codebase, first read `docs/agent/QUICKSTART.md` and follow that user-agent
workflow.

Run Portolan before broad manual architecture claims. Start with
`portolan context prepare --root <target-root> --out <context-dir> --profile cursor`
to get `agent-brief.md`, `answer-contract.md`, `query-plan.md`, `repos.json`,
`evidence-index.jsonl`, `tool-registry.json`, `oss-plan.json`, and
`gaps.jsonl`. From a Portolan source checkout, run `scripts/bootstrap-portolan`
and use `.portolan/bin/portolan` before falling back to
`go run ./cmd/portolan`.

Use `portolan map --root <target-root> --out <run-dir>` when graph artifacts are
needed after context preparation. It performs bounded local discovery over the
target root, direct child Git repositories, and `repos/*` Git repositories, but
external ecosystem completeness remains `unknown` without a manifest. Use
`portolan map --selection <selection.json> --out <run-dir>` only when a curated
local selection exists. Read `summary.json` and `graph-index.json` before full
`graph.json`; then read the generated context pack and map artifacts before
reporting.

Use `portolan graph slice --bundle <run-dir>` for bounded repo, edge-kind, or
finding-kind drill-downs before opening full `graph.json`.

`portolan map` can report exact duplicate source/config clusters. Do not treat
that as full copy/paste or near-clone coverage; use jscpd-style local outputs
from `tool-registry.json` when present, otherwise preserve that richer
duplication surface as `not_assessed`.

`portolan map` can report file-based configuration surfaces: env var names,
ports, container/workflow/manifests, feature flags, and secret references.
Secret values are intentionally absent from artifacts. Do not claim semantic
IaC/config correctness without local OSS evidence such as Semgrep output.

`portolan map` can report technical-debt candidate findings derived from local
evidence. Do not turn them into modernization, rewrite, release, or readiness
verdicts.

Use `answer-contract.md` as the required answer shape for broad CTO questions.
Answer from exact local evidence and gap ledger entries. Preserve `unknown`,
`cannot_verify`, and `not_assessed` instead of guessing. Do not fetch network
resources, mutate the repository, or collect credentials unless the user
explicitly approves that boundary. Build, packaging, configuration, release,
smoke-test, and integration repositories are valid targets; do not clone or
fetch referenced component source repositories unless the user explicitly
approves that boundary.

If OSS/tool outputs are absent, inspect `oss-plan.json` before claiming the
evidence cannot be produced. Run producer commands only with approval and only
when they write under the selected Portolan output directory.
Validate new OSS/tool-output adapter contracts with
`portolan adapter validate --in <adapter.json>` before relying on them.
Suggest only commands listed in the Portolan guide or generated
`answer-contract.md` / `oss-plan.json`; do not invent generic manifest flags or
commands such as `portolan context --manifest`.
